g moment of recognition, a moment in which interlocutors are positioned in relationship to each other and so may begin to construct a new lifeworld. By approaching human rights not as norms or laws, but as deliberative acts, Lyon conceives rights as relationships among people and as ongoing political and historical projects developing communal norms through global and cross-cultural interactions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aHuman rights. 0aPerformative (Philosophy). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aDeliberation human rights.  aDeliberation.  aRhetoric and Democratic.  aontoepistemological Rigoberto Menchú’s testimonio.  arhetoric performance democracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271062228?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271062228/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK